### TypeScript: Specifying a Narrowed Type

In TypeScript, you can use the `as` operator to tell the type system that you know a value may have multiple types, but in practice, it will only have a specific type. This technique is known as **narrowing**.

Here's an example:
```typescript
let value: string | number;

// Assign a string value
value = "Hello, world!";
console.log(typeof value); // "string"

// Assign a number value
value = 42;
console.log(typeof value); // "number"

// Narrow the type to string
if (typeof value === "string") {
  value = value.toUpperCase();
  console.log(value); // "HELLO, WORLD!"
}
```

In this example, the `value` variable is declared as a union type of `string` and `number`. However, when you use the `as` operator, you can tell the type system that you know the value will only be a `string`:

```typescript
// Narrow the type to string
if (typeof value === "string") {
  value = value.toUpperCase();
  console.log(value); // "HELLO, WORLD!"
}
```

This technique is useful when you have a variable that can be of multiple types, but you know it will only be of a specific type in a certain context.

