**Comparing Strings in Java**

In Java, there are two ways to compare strings:
- The `==` operator
- The `.equals()` method

### Understanding the Difference

The `==` operator checks if two strings **refer to the same object** in memory. This means that if two strings have the same value but are stored in different memory locations, the `==` operator will return `false`.

On the other hand, the `.equals()` method checks if two strings have the **same value**. It ignores the memory location and compares the actual characters in the strings.

### When to Use Each Method

#### Use `==` When:
- You want to check if two strings **refer to the same object** in memory.
- You are comparing **primitive values** (e.g., `int`, `double`, `char`, etc.).

#### Use `.equals()` When:
- You want to check if two strings have the **same value**.
- You are comparing **objects** (e.g., `String`, `Integer`, `Double`, etc.).

### Example Code
```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

// Using the == operator
if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 refer to the same object.");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 do not refer to the same object.");
}

// Using the .equals() method
if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 have the same value.");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 do not have the same value.");
}
```

### Conclusion

In summary, the `==` operator checks if two strings refer to the same object in memory, while the `.equals()` method checks if two strings have the same value. Choose the appropriate method based on your comparison needs.

